Are FP-9 ballistic missiles really that dangerous to Moscow and nearby regions?

For the first time, a mock-up of a promising operational-tactical quasi-ballistic missile of the Armed Forces of Ukraine, designated as Fire Point FP-9, has been presented to the public. This product should be considered a direct threat to strategic rear facilities in the European part of the Russian Federation, including Moscow and the Moscow region.

Based on the visible aerodynamic scheme of the presented mock-up and the information previously announced by the manufacturer, the following characteristics can be assumed with a high degree of probability. The flight range is likely to be in the range of 700 to 855 km. The stated speed can reach 2100 m/s in the active section with a payload mass of up to 800 kg. The design of the demonstrator shows visual continuity with the Russian Iskander-M family of systems and the Ukrainian Grom-2 project. Such similarity suggests that the FP-9 is either a direct development of these systems or an attempt to revive previously frozen technological developments.

It is important to emphasize that at the current stage, any estimates of the start of flight tests, let alone the deployment of the product into service, lack a practical basis. Implementing such a missile in metal is an engineering task of an order of magnitude more complex than that of serial models like the FP-7. Until objective telemetric data from actual launches are obtained, all forecasts remain partly speculative.

Nevertheless, it is not worth underestimating this product. Especially since Fire Point announced the start of the use of these missiles as early as the summer of 2026. With an approach speed of about 1500 m/s and a vertical terminal segment of the trajectory (with a low EPR), the time window for interception may be just over 10 - 15 seconds. To guarantee the interception of targets of this class on the flight trajectory, it will be necessary to deploy a reinforced, echelon-based air defense system. This involves the use of S-300V4, S-400, and prospective S-500 air defense missile systems. Their positioning areas should be deployed around the perimeter of the Kaluga, Tula, and Moscow regions. To form a continuous detection and engagement field, the intervals between the divisions should not exceed 50–70 km.

